THE FEDEX SPILL CLEAN UP SPECIALIST WAS CALLED AND THE PACKAGE WAS BAGGED TO BE BROUGHT BACK TO THE STATION FOR PROPER DISPOSITION. THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY MOVED THE CONSIGNEE'S (STONE CONTAINER CORP LOCATED A SHORT DISTANCE FROM INCIDENT SITE) UNLOADING TRACK TO PROVIDE FOR CONFINEMENT OF THE RELEASED MATERIAL WITHIN STONE CONTAINER'S POLLUTION CONTROL SYSTEM AND IMMEDIATE UPLOADING OF THE TANK CAR.  THE CONSIGNEE REPORTS THAT APPROXIMATELY 1,845 GALLONS OF LADDING WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANK CAR.  OF THE 1,845 GALLONS RELEASED. THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WILL BE CONTACTED BY STONER CONTAINER TO ARRANGE REPAIRS OF THE RESIDUE TANK CAR.

column168: PTL DRIVER CHANGED FROM RIGHT TO LEFT LANE TO PASS A CAR IN FRONT OF HER.  CAR THEN CAME INTO LEFT LANE TOWARD PTL.  PTL HIT HER BRAKES AND UNIT WENT OFF ROAD AND OVERTURNED.  TRAILER/TRACTOR LANDED ON ITS SIDE.  APPROXIMATELY 100 POUNDS OF AMMONIUM PERSULFATE LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE GROUND.  FUEL TANK ON TRACTOR WAS ALSO RUPTURED.  ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT INC. WAS CALLED TO HANDLE THE SPILL CLEANUP.  THE AMMONIUM PERSULFATE SPILL WAS TAKEN CARE OF BY EMI ON 1/9/1999.  OHIO EPA REQUESTED THAT EMI WAIT UNTIL 1/11/1999 TO CLEAN UP THE FUEL SPILL.  THE TRACTOR/ TRAILER WAS UPRIGHTED ON 1/9/1999.  EMI NOTIFIED THE NRC DUE TO THE FACT THE HIGHWAY HAD TO BE BLOCKED TO UPRIGHT EVERYTHING.  EMI WAS NOT ALLOWED TO DO THE FUEL SPILL CLEANUP THE WEEK OF THE 11TH DUE TO A SNOWSTORM.  I SPOKE WITH OHIO EPA AND WAS TOLD DUE TO THE WEATHER, IT WAS STILL IMPOSSIBLE FOR EMI TO COMPLETE.  OHIO EPA STATED THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND IN NO WAY A DANGER TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  OHIO EPA STATED THEY WOULD NOTIFY EMI WHEN THE CLEANUP COULD BE COMPLETED. EMI WAS ALLOWED TO DO THE CLEANUP ON 1/20/1999.  THE GROUND WAS RE-SODDED AND STRAW WAS PLACED OVER THE AREA.

ASHLAND DRIVER INFORMED UNLOADER THAT HE HAD 8 DRUMS AND 10 PALLETS. HE ALSO INFORMED UNLOADER THAT THE 10 PALLETS WERE ON SHORT SKIDS AND HIS FORKS ON HIS LIFT WILL PROTRUDE THROUGH THE PALLETS. ASHLAND DRIVER INFORMED UNLOADER THAT JUST AHEAD OF THE LAST SHORT PALLET WERE 3 X 55 GAL. DRUMS SO HE CAN ONLY GO IN HALF WAY INTO THE LAST PALLET. ASHLAND DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO GO INTO DRIVER'S ROOM TO WAIT TILL THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED. ANOTHER LIFT OPERATOR CAME OVER AND HELPED THE UNLOADING PROCESS AND WAS NOT INFORMED OF THE 3 DRUMS AHEAD OF THE LAST PALLET. HE NICKED ONE OF THE DRUMS AND PUT A SMALL HOLE IN ONE OF THE DRUMS. APPROXIMATELY 1 GAL.  OF PRODUCT LEAKED OUT. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY TURNED ON IT'S SIDE AND PUT IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO ASHLAND. SUBSEQUENT TO THIS INCIDENT ASHLAND HAS RETRAINED ALL IT'S MATERIAL HANDLERS IN LOAD SECUREMENT AND PUTTING DUNNAGE BETWEEN ANY DRUMS AND PALLETS THAT FORKS WILL PROTRUDE THROUGH.

PLASTIC JUGS ARE IN OUTER CARDBOARD CARTONS. INNER CONTAINER (JUGS) HAD TOTAL OF THREE JUGS WHICH HAD PROBLEMS WITH CLOSURES (LIDS). LIDS APPEAR TO BE CRACKED. SMALL AMOUNT OF ORGANIC PEROXIDE HAS LEAKED OUT OF THREE JUGS. HAS GOTTEN OUTER CARDBOARD BOX WET. THREE CARTONS TOTAL, PLACED INTO OVERPACK DRUM AND WILL BE SHIPPED BACK TO CARCIA GARCIA-ELF-ATOCHEM  CO-281-328-9436. FAULTY CAPS ON THREE INNER CONTAINERS. CAUSE OF RELEASE OF PRODUCT.

column168: DRIVER MADE ONE STOP PRIOR TO DELIVERY DESTINATION AT CONSIGNEE. OTHER PACKAGING SURROUNDING DRUM  WAS REMOVED LEAVING THE ONE (1) CONTAINER UNSECURED. THE DRIVER FAILED TO SECURE THE DRUM AGAINST MOVEMENT RELATIVE TO THE MOTION OF THE VEHICLE.THE DRIVER MADE A TURN AT AN INTERSECTION, CAUSING THE CONTAINER TO TIP OVER STRIKING THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK. THE FORCE OF THE LIQUID AGAINST THE HEAD  OF THE DRUM CAUSED THE CLOSURE TO RELEASE FROM THE OPENING, ALLOWING ALL LIQUID TO ESCAPE FROM THE CONTAINER. LOCAL RESPONSE  PERSONNEL WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE, COLLECTING ALL MATERIAL USING SODIUM BICARBONATE AS A NEUTRALIZER AND ABSORBENT. THIS SOLID, NEUTRALIZED MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED TO SUITABLE CONTAINERS AND TRANSPORTED FROM THE SCENE FOR LATER DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS DISCIPLINED BY SUSPENSION FOR FAILING TO COMPLY WITH COMPANY POLICY, SAFETY PROCEDURES, OPERATING GUIDELINES AND 49 CFR 177.834 (A). ADDITIONAL TRAINING FOR AND VERIFICATION OF PROPER LOADING IS NOW CONDUCTED TO ENSURE COMPLIANCE WITH THE REQUIREMENTS FOR TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

ARTHUR, TEXAS FIRE MARSHAL ORDERED AN EVACUATION OF APPROXIMATELY 30 PEOPLE FROM THE NEAREST HOUSING AREA AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE BEFORE THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS RIGHTED FROM THE DITCH. THERE WAS NO RUPTURE OF THE CARGO TANK AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT OR DURING RECOVERY AND NO LEAKAGE OCCURRED. THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED 1 1/2 MILES TO FINAL DESTINATION AND UNLOADED.

column168: ON JANUARY 2, 1999 AT 13:30, THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING EAST ON SECONDARY HIGHWAY 384 @ MILE MARKER 15. THE SPEED OF THE TRUCK WAS 4MPH WHEN THE DRIVER HIT BLACK ICE ON A CURVE AND THE TRUCK WAS UNABLE TO SAY ON THE ROAD. FOR THE PREVIOUS 59 MILES OF HIGHWAY WAS FREE FROM ICE. THE COUNTY HAD NOT SANDDED THE ROAD WHERE THE ACCIDENT HAD OCCURRED. THE RIVER RAN  INTO THE DITCH AND OVERTURNED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER. THE DRIVER CRAWLED OUT OF THE TRUCK AND GOT A RIDE BACK TO THE HOSPITAL IN HARDIN, MONTANA. THE SHERIFF, HIGHWAY PATROL,HANSER WRECKER AND MYSELF WAS NOTIFIED OF THE ACCIDENT. PRODUCT WAS LOST DUE TO  BOUBLE BULK HEAD DRAIN LEAK. ENVIRONMENTAL FIRM WAS ON THE SCENE WITHIN 24HRS. CLEANUP IS IN PROCESS.

WHILE MAKING A BULK ANHYDROUS AMMONIA DELIVERY FROM A CARGO TANK TO A REFRIGERATION RECEIVER TANK, A SEAL BROKE ON THE ELBOW THAT COMES OFF THE SWIVEL JOINT PART OF THE PIPING WHICH SUPPLIES AMMONIA TO THE DELIVERY HOSE REEL. WHEN THE SEAL BROKE, AMMONIA WAS RELEASED. OUR DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE DELIVERY OPERATION BY SHUTTING DOWN THE PUMP AND THE CUSTOMER ALSO ISOLATED HIS PROCESS. OUR DELIVERY WAS EXPOSED TO LIQUID AND VAPOR AMMONIA; SKIN EXPOSURE AND RESPIRATORY EXPOSURE. HE WAS TREATED AND SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED AT LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR MINOR BURNS TO FACE, NECK,BACK AND BACK OF ARM AS WELL AS FOR RESPIRATORY IRRITATION. CARGO TRAILER WAS SENT TO A REPAIR SHOP WHERE THE HOSE REEL SWIVEL SEAL WAS REPLACED.

column168: CUSTIMER PETER BOURNE ORDERED A FULL TRANSPORT LOAD OF KEROSENE DELIVERED INTO HIS BOURNE'S INC. LOCATION (TANK FARM) LOCATED ON RT 100 IN WATERBURY. DRIVER LIONEL CHARBONNEAU ARRIVED, HOOKED UP THE HOSE AND STARTED TO PUMP OFF HIS LOAD.  TANK HE WAS PUMPING INTO WOULD NOT HOLD THE FULL TRANSPORT LOAD AND BEGAN TO OERFLOW.  DRIVER WAS RIGHT THERE, RAN TO SHUT OFF HIS PUMP.  ORIGINALLY IT WAS THOUGHT (BY THE DRIVER) THAT LESS THAN 20 GALLONS OVERFLOWED, BUT THEN WE RECALCULATED USING THE RATE AT WHICH HIS PUMP WAS PUMPING OFF PRODUCT AND THE TIME TO SHUT IT OFF WE ESTIMATE 40 TO 50 GALLONS OVERFLOWED.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY MADE ATTEMPTS TO CONTAIN SPILLAGE WHICH WERE DEEMED SUCCESSFUL.  HE CALLED HIS DISPATCH AND OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEAN-UP CREW WAS CALLED.  SPILL WAS REPORTED TO OWNER AS WELL AS STATE AND FEDERAL OFFICIALS.

column168: During normal flat switching operation to double up a train for the Wisconsin Central, Tank car CGBX 006369 was kicked into track 11 at the Illinois Central Railroad's "A" yard in Homewood, Illinois, by an IC switch crew. An IC carman was standing in the clear immediately adjacent to the movement. When tank car CGBX 006369 struck the cut of cars to be coupled into the safety relief valve operated and reseated itself which caused a release of sodium hydroxide solution. Several drops of the product hit the IC carman on the nose and right hand. The car man, believing it was water or snow off the top of the car, laced up the train and was walking back to the yard office when the spots on his nose and hand began to burn. The car man called for a supervisor and began washing off the areas on his hand and nose with soap and water. When the supervisor arrived he took the carman to a local hospital where he was given first aid by washing the areas with soap and water and then a burn cream was applied. Doctor released the car man back to full duty and told him to follow up with his own doctor in a few days. Tank car was isolated awaiting a test of the safety relief valve. Rescar arrived and tested the valve several times but could not  find anything wrong with it. Tank car CGBX 006369 was then washed down with vinegar and water and then returned to transportation without further incident.

TANK CAR SPLIT OPEN AFTER IMPACT IN CLASSIFICATION YARD ACFX76608 JANUARY 14, 1999 ALBANY DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 1355 HOURS, THURSDAY, JANUARY 14, 1999 AT CONRAIL'S SELKIRK YARD IN SELKIRK, NEW YORK, A CONRAIL CONDUCTOR DISCOVERED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR ACFX 76608 CONTAINING HEPTANES. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1415 HOURS, THURSDAY, JANUARY 14, 1999 CONRAIL'S GENERAL CAR FOREMAN AND DISTRICT TERMINAL SUPERINTENDENT ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND UPON EXAMINING THE CAR THEY DETERMINED THE TANK CAR WAS SPLIT AT THE A-END FROM THE A-END BODY SILL SADDLE PAD EXTENDING LONGITUDINAL 40 INCHES. AT APPROXIMATELY 1500 HOURS, THURSDAY JANUARY 14, 1999 MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND THEY IMMEDIATELY SET UP CONTAINMENT AND ATTEMPTED TO SEAL THE CRACK TO MINIZE RELEASE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1600 HOURS, CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER ARRIVED AT THE SIDE AND ARRANGED FOR THE TRUCKS AND BEGAN VACUUMING THE PRODUCT. APPROXIMATELY 24091 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS PUMPED FROM THE TANK CAR TO THE TANK TRUCK. AT APPROXIMATELY 2110 HOURS THE CAR WAS EMPTIED. MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL BEGAN GROUND REMEDIATION AND CLEANED AND PURGED THE TANK CAR. THE TANK CAR WILL BE HOME SHOPPED FOR TANK REPLACEMENT.

LOAD DELIVERED TO PARKER WAREHOUSE AND IT WAS NOTICED DURING INSPECTI0N OF LOAD THAT A BUNG FROM A DRUM WAS NOT PROPERLY CLOSED. column168: THE DRUM IN QUESTION CONTAINED A MIXTURE OF INORGANIC ACIDS THAT HAD BEEN CONSOLIDATED FOR EFFICIENCY OF TRANSPORTATION AND  AND DISPOSAL. AT THE TIME OF CONSOLIDATION AND OF LOADING, THE DRUMS EXHIBITED NO EVIDENCE OF INCOMPATIBILITY, REACTION, OR PRESURE BUILDUP. THE TRANSPORT TRUCK (A FLAT/ STRAKE-BED TRUCK) PICKING THIS DRUM UP COMPLETED LOADING AT APPROXIMATELY 1335 ON 12 JANUARY. AT THE DRIVER'S NEXT PICKUP LOCATION, HE STOPPED HIS VEHICLE,AND HEARD A LOUD HISSING SOUND COMING FROM BEHIND HIM. HE REALIZED THAT LIQUID WAS SPRAYING FROM ONE OF THE DRUMS IN HIS LOAD. THE  DRIVER SECURED HIS VEHICLE, CLEARED THE AREA, AND CONTACTED THE RHO-CHEM OFFICE AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE DRUM IN QUESTION CONTAINED A MIXTURE OF WASTE INORGANIC ACIDS,JOSTLING IN TRANSPORTATION MAY HAVE CAUSED MIXING OF LAYERS OR OF SEDIMENTS WHICH CAUSED A REACTION, RESULTING IN HEAT AND PRESSURE BUILDING IN THE DRUM. EVENTUALLY, THE PRESSURE INCREASED TO THE POINT WHERE THE DRUM SPLIT A SEAM, ALLOWING LIQUID TO SPRAY OUT OF THE DRUM. CLEANUP AND DECONTAMINATION WERE CONDUCTED BY RHO-CHEM PERSONNEL IN ASSOCIATION WITH AND UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT (HAZ MAT AND HEALTH HAZ MAT). SPILLED LIQUID WAS ABSORBED USING AN INORGANIC CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT. SURFACES WERE WASHED A PRESSURE WASHER. ACIDS WERE NEUTRALIZED USING SODIUM BICARBONATE AND SODIUM CARBONATE. ALL RINSEWATERS AND CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT WERE COLLECTED AND DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH HAZARDOUS WASTE REGULATIONS. A COPY OF THE MANIFEST IS ATTACHED. THE DRUM INVOLVED WAS ONE OF TWO DESRIBED ON PAGE TWO, SECTION 28, LINEB.

CONSIGNEE'S TANKS ARE INSIDE AND ARE OUT OF SIGHT FROM DRIVER WHILE UNLOADING. CONSIGNEE MIS-GAUGED THEIR TANK AND APPROX. 10 GALLONS OVERFLOWED. CONSIGNEE ASSUMED FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR SPILL AND CLEANUP.

WHILE MOVING A PALLET OF METAL DRUMS AT A TRANSFER FACILITY, ONE OF THE DRUMS FELL FROM THE PALLET AND THE LID POPPED OFF. FOUR GALLONS OF WASTE SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE FLOOR IN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. THE WASTE WAS ABSORBED AND PLACED INTO AN APPROVAL CONTAINER. THE DAMAGED LID WAS REPLACED ON THE ORIGINAL DRUM. THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 40 POUNDS  OF WASTE THAT WAS, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 2120 SOUTH YALE ST, SANTA ANA, CA FOR CONSOLIDATION AND TRANSFER TO A RECYCLING FACILITY. THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO ENSURE DRUMS WERE STABLE ON PALLETS PRIOR TO MOVING THEM.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: WHILE BACKING UP A TRUCK TO THE DOCK TO UNLOAD HIS VEHICLE, AN UNSECURED 55 GALLON DRUM SHIFTED AND TIPPED OFF A PALLET.  THIS CAUSED THE DRUM LID TO COME LOOSE AND ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF WASTE TO BE SPILLED INTO THE CARGO AREA OF THE TRUCK. THE TRUCK DRIVER ABSORBED THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND SECURED THE LID BACK ON THE DRUM.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO AN APPROVED CONTAINER FOR STORAGE AND LATER DISPOSAL.  THIS RELEASE GENERATED TWENTY POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LAGRANGE ROAD, SMITHFIELD, KY FOR RECYCLING.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO ENSURE ALL CARGO IS SECURED TO PREVENT SHIFTING AND DAMAGE TO CARGO.

A DRIVER INSPECTING HIS LOAD NOTICED A LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE DOOR OF THE TRAILER.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE  CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK, SEAL THE LEAK, AND CLEANUP THE SPILLED MATERIAL INSIDE AND OUTSIDE THE TRAILER.  UPON ENTERING THE TRAILER THE CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THAT A 330 GALLON PORTABLE TANK(TOTE) HAD BEEN CRUSHED BECAUSE IT WAS LOADED TOO CLOSE TO ANOTHER CONTAINER.  THE LEAKING LEAK WAS PLUGGED AND THE WASTE LEFT INSIDE THE TOTE WAS TRANSFERRED TO A NEW CONTAINER.  THE SPILLED  MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED INTO APPROVED CONTAINERS FOR STORAGE AND DISPOSAL.  THIS SPILL GENERATED 1500 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3527 WHISKEY BOTTOM ROAD, LAUREL, MD FOR CONSOLIDATION AND TRANSFER TO A TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL FACILITY.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO ENSURE CARGO IS LOADED TO AVOID CONTACT BETWEEN CONTAINERS.

A DRIVER INSPECTING HIS LOAD DISCOVERED A 55 GALLON DRUM WITH A DEFECTIVE SEAL THAT HAD ALLOWED ONE GALLON OF WASTE TO LEAK INTO THE BACK OF HIS TRUCK.  THE DRIVER REPLACED THE SEAL AND ABSORBED AND PACKED THE SPILL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL.  THIS SPILL GENERATED TEN POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 500 BATTLEGROUND ROAD, LA PORTE, TX FOR CONSOLIDATION AND TRANSFER TO A FUEL BLENDING FACILITY. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1755 HRS, 01-21-1999, ON THE CHICAGO LINE AT MP 201 IN NELLISTON, NY, CONRAIL TRAIN NFSE1 DERAILED 32 CARS. OF THE TWENTY CARS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THAT DERAILED, ONLY ONE TANK CAR UTLX 37485 RELEASED PRODUCT. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. APPROXIMATELY 150 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FROM THEIR HOMES FOR APPROXIMATELY 24 HRS. DURING THE DERAILMENT, HAND BRAKE OPERATING STEM OF TANK CAR CITX 33376 PUNCTURED TANK SHELL OF UTLX 37485 CREATING A SMALL PINHOLE ALLOWING GAS VAPORS TO ESCAPE. AT APPROXIMATELY 0400 HRS, 01-22-1999, HULCHER AND REACT, ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTORS ARRIVED AT THE SITE. THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANK CARS AND TRUCKS IN ADDITION TO BEING FLARED ON SITE. THE TANK CAR WAS CLEANED AND SCRAPPED ON SITE. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS DELIVERED TO  DESTINATION VIA TRUCK. THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT WAS A MECHANICAL WHEEL FAILURE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1600 HRS., SATURDAY, 02-06-1999, ALL PRODUCT TRANSFERS WERE COMPLETED. THE FOLLOWING IS A LIST OF TANK CARS INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT THAT DID NOT RELEASE ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND WERE TRANSFERRED, CLEANED AND PURGED ON SITE.

column168: AN EMPLOYEE OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF NATX 21263.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT, AND PLACED IN A ISOLATION TRACK EQUIPPED WITH A CATCH PAN.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO MAKE REPAIRS TO THE CAR.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (TOBOV) WAS LOOSE.  REQUIRING A QUARTER-TURN TO TIGHTENED THE VALVE.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS ALSO LOOSE.   THE CAP REQUIRED A HALF-TURN TO TIGHTEN.  ONCE THE TOBOV AND BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WERE TIGHTENED, THE CAR CEASED TO LEAK.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.  APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP WAS COLLECTED INTO HE CATCH PAN UNDER THE CAR

column168: THE TRAINMASTER FOUND TANK CAR PLCX 129011 LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN COLLIER, VA., SOMEHOW THE PIN WAS NOT SECURE AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE WORKED ITS WAY OPEN.  THE TRAINMASTER CLOSED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  AFTER THE VALVE WAS RE-SECURED IT WA DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS ALSO A SMALL LEAK AT THE TOP OF TH FLANGE THAT CONNECTS TO THE TANK CAR THIS LEAK COULD NOT BE STOPPED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, CLEAN HARBORS, RESPONDED TO PERFORM CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES. WE RECOVERY APPROX., 200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM AN ADJACENT DITCH. THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE LEAKING TANK CAR INTO HIGHWAY TANKERS WHICH WERE DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  IT IS NOT KNOWN WHEN OR WHERE THE CAR BEGAN TO LEAK.  ACCORDING TO THE SHIPPER'S OUTAGE CALCULATIONS, THERE IS APPROX., 1900 GALLONS OF PRODUCT UNACCOUNTED FOR.

column168: ON JANUARY 16, 1999, AT APPROXIMATELY 1055 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, AFCX200120, RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED PETROLEUM DISTILLATE, N.O.S., WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS'S GREENVILLE, TEXAS YARD.  KCS DALLAS, TEXAS, TRAINMASTER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND TIGHTENED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP, STOPPING THE LEAK AT 1120 HOURS ON THAT SAME DAY.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE LEAK AND SUBSEQUENT REPAIRS, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DESTINATION AT 1127 HOURS ON JANUARY 16, 1999. DEFECTIVE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND CAP.

ON JANUARY 21, 1999, AT APPROXIMATELY 1715 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, REPORTING NUMBERS NATX300087, LOADED WIT PETROLEUM DISTILLATE, N.O.S. WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS'S BATON ROUGE, LOUISIANA RAIL YARD.  THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS NOTIFIED TO RESPOND TO AND REPAIR THE TANK CAR. THE SHIPPER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND MADE REPAIRS TO A DEFECTIVE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE, CORRECTING THE LEAK.  THE TANK CAR WAS THE ORDERED BACK INTO THE SHIPPERS PLANT FOR FURTHER REPAIRS.

A SUPERVISOR TOLD ME THERE WERE TWO LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGES IN A TRAILER AT THE EAST UNLOAD DOCK #31.  I WENT TO THE TRAILER WITH THE PROPER EQUIPMENT, SAW TWO WET BOXES AND RETRIEVED THEM.  I BROUGHT THEM TO PSC AREA FOR PROCESSING.

ILLINOIS CENTRAL YARD EMPLOYEES REPORTED THAT THEY SMELLED AMMONIA IN THE IC "A" YARD, HOMEWOOD, ILLINOIS AROUND TANK CAR GATX 080777. ALL OPERATIONS IN THE AREA WERE STOPPED AND A IC HAZ-MAT TEAM WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE.  DURING THE INSPECTION OF THE RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED CAR IT WAS DISCOVERED THE 2" PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE SLIP-TUBE GAUGING DEVICE ASSEMBLY WAS LOOSE AND WAS ALLOWING A SMALL VAPOR RELEASE.  THE NUT WAS TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  CAR WAS OFFERED BACK TO TRANSPORTATION FOR MOVEMENT ON TO CONSIGNEE.

DEFECTIVE AND IMPROPERLY APPLIED MANWAY COVER GASKET, RTMX 3160, JANUARY 16, 1999, PHILADELPHIA DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0520 HOURS, SATURDAY, JANUARY 16, 1999, AT CONRAIL'S ALLENTOWN YARD IN ALLENTOWN, PA, A CONRAIL CAR DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEE NOTED AN ODOR AROUND TANK CAR RTMX 3160 CONTAINING WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (ACETONE, TOLUENE).  ON SATURDAY, JANUARY 16, 1999, REACT,  AN ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT IT HAD A DEFECTIVE AND IMPROPERLY APPLIED MANWAY COVER GASKET.  ON JANUARY 18, 1999, THE SHIPPER, MARISOL ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND REPLACED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET. THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED, OKAYED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND SENT TO DESTINATION.

column17: P T C OF MOUNT AIRY INC
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO AN ABOVE GROUND TANK AT THIS LOCATION. THE CUSTOMER HAD ORDERED 7500 GALLONS OF FUEL. ACCORDING TO THE GAUGE ON THE TANK, IT WOULD ONLY HOLD 6000 GALLONS. BEFORE THE 6000 GALLONS HAD BEEN UNLOADED, THE TANK HAD OVERFILLED AND PRODUCT CAME OUT OF VENT. THE DRIVER SHUT OFF FLOW OF THE PRODUCT. THE SPILLED PRODUCT SHOULD HAVE GONE INTO IT A CONTAINMENT DIKE BUT THE DIKE HAD A COVERING OVER IT TO PREVENT RAIN FROM ENTERING INTO IT AND THE  COVERING ALSO PREVENTED THE OVERFLOING DIESEL FROM ENTERING INTO IT. THE AST AT THIS LOCATION DID NOT HAVE AN ALARM ON THE TANK OR A MEANS OF STOPPING DELIVERY OF PRODUCT AT 95% CAPACITY AS REQUIRED BY EPA REGULATIONS. WE FEEL THAT OUR DRIVER DID EVERYTHING IN HIS POWER TO PREVENT A SPILL AND BECAUSE OF THE LACK OF NONADHERENCE TO EPA REGULATIONS, PTC DOES NOT ACCEPT LIABILITY FOR THIS INCIDENT AND WE WILL NOT RETURN TO THIS LOCATION UNTIL THE AST HAS BEEN BROUGHT UP TO REGULATORY STANDARDS.

column168: THE CAM LOCK FITTING ON THE HOSE WAS CRACKED. PRODUCT DILUTED AND WASHED INTO PLANT SYSTEM.

A LOAD OF FUEL OIL WAS BEING TRANSFERRED TO AN UNDER GROUND STORAGE TANK. TANK WAS UNKNOWINGLY OVERFILLED, CAUSING PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED THROUGH THE VENT LINE. RELEASE WAS NOT DISCOVERED UNTIL 1-21-1999 (DUE TO LOCATION OF UNDERGROUND TANK). THE RELEASE WAS REPORTED TO MICHIGAN DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND THE TANK AND ASSOCIATED CONTAMINATED SOIL HAS BEEN REMOVED.

AFTER RECEIVING OKAY TO UNLOAD, DRIVER HOOKED UP A 3" FEMALE TO A 3" MALE FITTING AND STARTED TO AIR-OFF CARGO TANK. A DRIP STARTED BY FITTING. DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND STARTED TO REMOVE HOSE. THERE  WAS PRESSURE TRAPPED BETWEEN EXTERNAL VALVE ON TRAILER AND CONSIGNEE'S LINE AND PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT. DRIVER FAILED TO WEAR HIS PPE AND GOT PRODUCT ON HIMSELF. HE WASHED DOWN AT SAFETY SHOWER AND EYE WASH AND WAS SENT TO CONSIGNEE'S EMERGENCY FACILITY. DRIVER WAS ISSUED A WARNING LETTER FOR FAILURE TO FOLLOW PROCEDURE AND FAILURE TO WEAR PPE AS INSTRUCTED.

A RAIL TANK CAR CONTAINING ALUMINUM CHLORIDE SOLUTION WAS IN THE PROCESS OF BEING UNLOADED AT OUR PLANT IN SPOKANE,WA. A PLANT OPERATOR IN THE AREA AND NOTICED THE PRODUCT DISCHARGE HOSE HAD RUPTURED AND PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM HOSE. THE OPERATOR QUICKLY CLOSED THE PRODUCT DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE RAIL CAR THEN CLOSED  THE PRODUCT VALVE AT THE STORAGE TANK. THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE HOSE THEN DRAINED ONTO THE CONCRETE PADS NEXT TO THE TRACKS. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT ABOUT TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND, AND THREE GALLONS ON THE CONCRETE PAD ABOVE AND ALONG SIDE THE RAIL SIDING AND ANOTHER TWENTY GAL. INSIDE THE TANK FARM CONTAINMENT AREA. THE AFFECTED AREA OUTSIDE THE CONTAINMENT AREA WAS WASHED DOWN AND PUMPED INTO THE ALUM PLANT TO BE BLENDED INTO DILUTION WATER USED IN ALUM PROCESSING. AFTER THE INCIDENT THE EQUIPMENT WAS INSPECTED AT THE SITE OF THE RUPTURE. THE HOSE WAS FOUND TO BE SCUFFED AND FLATTENED IN THE AREA OF THE RUPTURE, IT APPEARS THE HOSE WAS PROBABLY RUN OVER BY A FORK LIFT PRIOR TO USE. WE ARE CURRENTLY DEVELOPING AN SOP FOR THIS TYPE OF OPERATION, INCLUDED WILL BE A DETAILED CHECK LIST AND OPERATOR TRAINING TO ASSURE ALL EQUIPMENT IS PROPERLY INSPECTED PRIOR TO USE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: (A-B) WHILE TRYING TO PASS ANOTHER VEHICLE ON I-65 NEAR KEEDNER TOWNSHIP, THE DRIVER STRUCK ANOTHER TRUCK AND LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE.  HE WENT OFF THE ROAD AND INTO A DITCH WHERE THE TRUCK FLIPPED ONTO ITS SIDE.  THE STATE POLICE, STATE DOT AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT.  THEY SECURED THE AREA AND CALLED A LOCAL CONTRACTOR, DBS, TO MAKE THE ENTRY INTO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER TO CONTAIN ANY SPILLED MATERIAL.  TWO DIFFERENT WASTES WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THESE CONTAINERS WERE CRUSHED DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING DURING THE ACCIDENT.  THE TWO WASTE STREAMS WERE AN AQUEOUS BRAKE CLEANER WITH TETRACHLOROETHYLENE AND PAINT RELATED MATERIAL.  ANOTHER CONTRACTOR, CLEAN HARBORS, WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO REPACKAGE ANY LEAKING CONTAINERS AND PACKAGE THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT LAID DOWN BY THE 1ST RESPONDERS.  THEY ALSO MANAGED THE TRANSFER OF THE LOAD TO A NEW TRUCK AND TRAILER DISPATCHED BY SAFETY KLEEN.  THE TRUCK WAS TOWED TO TRUCK AND TRAILER IN HAMMOND, IN. AS THE TRUCK WAS BEING TOWED OUT OF THE DITCH, THE FUEL TANKS STARTED TO LEAK DIESEL FUEL ONTO THE GROUND.  CLEAN HARBORS CONTAINED THESE RELEASES AND IS IN PROCESS OF REMEDIATING THE AREA.  200 POUNDS OF WASTE WAS GENERATED FROM THE SPILLED MATERIAL IN THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  THIS MATERIAL, THE OVERPACKED DRUMS AND THE REST OF THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER VEHICLE AND TRANSPORTED TO THE CONSIGNEE ADDRESS - 633 E 138TH ST DOLTON, IL 60419 FOR DISPOSAL.  THIS TRUCK WAS CARRYING A FULL LOAD THAT WAS MANIFESTED ON APPROX 100 DIFFERENT SHIPPING PAPERS.  DUE TO THE URGENCY OF THE SITUATION AND THE OVERRIDING CONCERN OF GETTING THE SPILLED MATERIAL CLEANED UP AND THE LOAD TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER VEHICLE, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE OTHER RESPONDERS DID NOT MATCH UP AND THE LEAKING CONTAINERS TO SPECIFIC MANIFESTS.  FOR THAT REASON ITEMS 11 AND 32 OF THIS REPORT ARE NOT KNOWN AND COPIES OF THE MANIFESTS ARE NOT INCLUDED WITH THIS REPORT.  AT YOUR REQUEST THE MANIFESTS FOR THE ENTIRE LOAD CAN BE PROVIDED.  TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE OF SUCH AN ACCIDENT SAFETY KLEEN IS INVESTIGATING THE ACCIDENT.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN SUSPENDED FROM HIS DUTIES DURING THIS INVESTIGATION.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO PASS A SLOW MOVING TRAILER ON THE LEFT WHEN A FOUR WHEEL PASSENGER VEHICLE CUT OUT AND AROUND DRIVERS UNIT TO PASS HIM. IN AN EFFORT TO AVOID HITTING THE FOUR WHEEL PASSENGER VEHICLE OUR DRIVER SWERVED HARD BACK TO THE RIGHT. IN DOING SO OUR DRIVER'S UNIT GOT AGAINST THE GUARDRAIL AND DO TO THE FACT THAT HE WAS HAULING LIQUID BULK PRODUCT THE UNIT WAS PULLED BY INERITA OVER THE RAILING AND INTO THE DITCH BOTTOM COMING TO REST ON THE UNITS TOP. THE INITIAL IMPACT WITH THE GROUND CAUSED THE TRAILER TO BEGIN A SLOW LEAK. IN THE PROCESS OF ATTEMPTING TO OFFLOAD THE WRECKED TRAILER SO THAT IT COULD BE UPRIGHTED WE EXPERIENCED A PUMP FAILURE WHICH SUBSEQUENTLY RESULTED IN LOSE OF THE ENTIRE LOAD INTO THE DITCH. DUE TO THE QUICK THINKING OF THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT SEVERAL BOOMS WERE STRETCHED ACROSS THE OPENING OF THE DITCH ALMOST IMMEDIATELY AND NO CONTAMINATE WAS ALLOWED TO ESCAPE PRIOR TO OUR PICKING IT AND ANY CONTAMINATED SURFACES UP AND REMOVING TO AN APPROPRIATE LOCATION. WE ALSO REMEDITATED THE SCENE BACK TO ITS ORIGINAL CONDITION OR BETTER WHICH IS WHY THERE IS NO DOLLAR LOSS FIGURE ENTERED FOR PRIVATE/PUBLIC PROPERTY LOSS

column168: UPON ARRIVING AT CUSTOMER LOCATION IN HASTINGS, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED AN EMPTY SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TOTE WITH A CRACKED VALVE. HE THEN CONTACTED DPC-OMAHA'S PLANT MANAGER. AFTER GETTING THE DETAILS FROM HIS DRIVER, THE PLANT MANAGER HAD THE LOADING AREA INSPECTED FOR SIGNS OF LEAKAGE WHILE HE CONTACTED THE CORPORATE S, H, E DEPARTMENT OF THE INCIDENT. THE INITIAL REPORT WAS TAKEN AND NRC AND DEQ  WAS CONTACTED. DPC BELIEVES THE COLD WEATHER CAUSED THE VALVE TO CRACK. NOTE ON RELEASE LOCATION: EMPTY TOTE WAS DISCOVERED IN HASTINGS. TRUCK WAS FUELED IN YORK. NE. AND NO LEAK WAS NOTICEABLE AT THAT TIME. IT IS BELIEVED LEAK OCCURRED ON ONE OF THE FOLLOWING: HIGHWAY 80 BETWEEN YOUR AND GRAND ISLAND OR HIGHWAY 281 BETWEEN GRAND ISLAND AND HASTINGS. WEATHER CONDITIONS ON THE ROADWAYS (MELTING SNOW) WOULD HAVE MADE IT DIFFICULT TO DETECT THE LEAK FROM THE TOTE DURING TRANSPORT; HOWEVER, THE DRIVER WAS NEVER FLAGGED DOWN BY A PASSING MOTORIST INDICATING THERE WAS A PROBLEM WITH THE TRUCK OR ITS CONTENTS.

column168: I SPOKE TO THE I/C EMPLOYEE WHO WAS SORTING OUR 8-N FREIGHT THAT NIGHT AND SHE REMEMBERS THAT THIS BOX WAS ON THE FLOOR BECAUSE SHE HAD TO SLIDE IT OUT OF THE WAY TO GET TO TWO SMALLER BOXES.  SHE DIDN'T NOTICE ANYTHING AT THAT TIME.  SHE CAME INTO THE OFFICE AND WHEN SHE WENT BACK OUT INTO THE WAREHOUSE SHE NOTICED THE SMELL.  THAT'S WHEN SHE SAW THE BOX WAS LEAKING FLUID ONTO THE FLOOR.  SHE THEN CAME BACK INTO THE OFFICE AND ADVISED ME OF THE SITUATION.  WE MOVED THE SURROUNDING FREIGHT AWAY FROM THE BOX BEFORE IT WAS KNOWN TO BE A HAZMAT SHIPMENT.  AS A RESULT SIX PEOPLE WERE BRIEFLY EXPOSED TO THE FUMES.  TWO WERE I/C EMPLOYEES: SAMANTHA NELSON AND LAURA DELOS SANTO.  THREE WERE AIRBORNE EMPLOYEES: PATTI MACE, SANDY THOLEN AND MYSELF.  THE SIXTH PERSON WAS OUR JANITORIAL SERVICE PERSON: VANESSA JONES WHO WAS TAKING THE TRASH OUT THROUGH ANOTHER DOOR BEFORE WE WERE ABLE TO ADVISE HER OF THE SITUATION AND BRING HER BACK INTO THE OFFICE.  THERE HAVE BEEN NO REPORTS OF ILL EFFECTS FROM THIS BRIEF EXPOSURE AND NO ONE CAME IN DIRECT CONTACT WITH THE PRODUCT.  AFTER IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE A HAZ SPILL ALL PERSONNEL WERE EVACUATED FROM THE AREA. I THEN CALLED AND LEFT A MESSAGE WITH EXPRESS SUPPORT ADVISING THEM OF THE SPILL.  I ALSO CALLED CHEMTREC AND WAS FAXED A COPY OF THE MSDS.  I WAS ADVISED BY THEM TO VENTILATE THE AREA.  I WENT BACK INTO THE WAREHOUSE AND OPENED SEVERAL BAY DOORS TO DO SO.  I WAS THEN PUT INTO CONTACT WITH TOM TAGART, WHO IN TURN PUT ME INTO CONTACT WITH GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL AND THEY SENT A CREW OUT TO CLEAN THE SPILL.

ALSO ADVISED TO CALL SHIPPER, AND ORGIN STATION FOR PAPERWORK,MSDS, DIRECTIONS. KARNELL SELL CALLED EDS STATION ANS SPOKE WITH MATT. ADVISED EDS WE NEEDED COPY OF THE HAZ DEC. KARNELL CALLED FISHER HEALTH CARE AFTER FINDING ACROSS ORGANICS DID NOT HAVE A LISTING WITH INFORMATION. DEBBIE WAS THE POINT OF CONTACT AND SHE SAID THEY WOULD FAX US THE MSDS. THEY ALSO ADVISED NOT TO DELIVER THE PACKAGE TO THE CNSE. THEY MENTIONED IF WE COULD JUST DESTROY IT AND WE SAID NO IT IS HAZ MAT. CLEAN UP OF THE SPILL ENED. RON MKE/DFSM

column168: Train crew discovered leak on tank car ACFX 82055 in north yard, track 13, at approximately 1600 cst and notified the control station (yard office). Yardmaster on duty, James McNeil, notified Chemtrex and ASD Protection. ASD Protection notified Cliff Wright of ASD Environmental health and safety. The area was closed to rail traffic. Susan White, Three-E company, contacted the yard office and said a response team from Ferguson-Harbour (Spanish fort, Alabama) was on the way. John Crosby was in charge of the response team. The belly ring on ACFX 82055 was loose and the contents of the tank car were leaking. The belly plug was tightened and absorbent pads placed on the contaminated area. After they were sure that the plug would not leak, the area was cleaned and opened up for rail traffic. Susan White can be reached at (800) 468-1760. John Crosby can be reached at (334) 626-3295. Alabama state docks.
Overfill occurred, also some oil seeped from threads at the tank causing outage which was contained and is still being cleaned up and properly disposed of.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: A WET CELL WHEELCHAIR BATTERY WAS INADVERTENTLY ACCEPTED AND IMPROPERLY PACKAGED FOR TRANSPORTATION ON FLIGHT 1878 FROM LAS TO OAK. A MISCOMMUNICATION THAT THE WHEELCHAIR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A GEL CELL NON-SPILLABLE BATTERY WAS TRANSMITTED TO THE RAMP SUPERVISOR IN CHARGE OF INSPECTING AND LOADING THE WHEELCHAIR ABOARD THE AIRCRAFT.THE SUPERVISOR DISCONNECTED THE BATTERY FOR SHORT CIRCUIT PREVENTION AND PROCEEDED TO LOAD THE WHEELCHAIR INTO THE AIRCRAFT UNDER THE ASSUMPTION THAT THE BATTERY WAS NONSPILLABLE. IN THE PROCESS OF LEARNING THE WHEELCHAIR BACKWARD FOR ENTRY INTO THE AIRCRAFT BIN. APPROXIMATELY 6-8 OUNCES OF BATTERY ACID SPILLED OUT ONTO THE BIN FLOOR.UPON REALIZATION THAT THE LIQUID WAS BATTERY ACID, THE EMPLOYEES NOTIFIED A/C MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL WHO NEUTRALIZED THE LIQUID AND DECONTAMINATED THE BIN. THEY THEN CLEANED THE BATTERIES AND PACKAGED THEM FOR TRANSPORTATION. AT THIS POINT THE LAS MANAGER OF RAMP AND OPERATIONS CONTACTED SOUTHWEST CUSTOMER SERVICE COORDINATORS IN DALLAS TO REPORT THE INCIDENTS. THEY WERE INSTRUCTED TO NOTIFY THEIR LOCAL CASFO. IT WAS AFTER HOURS WHEN THE CASFO WAS CONTACTED AND ACTUAL COMMUNICATION OF THE INCIDENT OCCURED THE FOLLOWING DAY TO AGENT CAROL POISON. THE RAMP SUPERVISOR IN CHARGE OF INSPECTION AND TRANSPORTATION OF THE WHEELCHAIR WAS GIVEN A LETTER OF INSTRUCTION AND ALL RAMP SUPERVISORS WERE RETRAINED ON THE COMPANY WHEELCHAIR PROCEDURES ON FEBRUARY 4TH DURING THEIR SUPERVISOR MEETING.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 HOURS, JANUARY 12,1999, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED. SAVAGE AND MONTGOMERY TANK LINES UNLOADED THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE TANK CAR AND TRANSFERRED IT INTO GATX 11656. EMERGENCY RESPONSE/MANAGEMENT FOR MITSUBISHI WAS DIRECTED BY TIM TURNER, SAFETY MANAGER, WHO ASSUMED THE POSITION OF INCIDENT COMMANDER. MR. TURNER WAS ASSISTED BY JOHN M. REINHARTS, DIRECTOR OF ENVIRONMENTAL AND SAFETY AND MICHAEL K. HUDSON, ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALIST. MR. JOE SMITH, SAFETY DIRECTOR OF PHILIP SERVICES OUT OF MOBILE, ALABAMA (PRIME CONTRACTOR ON THIS PROJECT) WAS AT THE SCENE SHORTLY AFTER THE INCIDENT BEGAN. A DECISION WAS MADE AT THE SCENE TO CONTRACT THE SERVICES OF UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, L.L.C., TO TRANSFER MATERIAL BACK TO MITSUBISHI HOLDING TANK AND  OTHER EMERGENCY MEASURES. MR. HUNTER GEORGE FROM UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL'S OFFICE IN SARALAND, ALABAMA WAS THE COORDINATOR.3:20 p.m. MR. BEAL SPOKE TO MICHAEL HUDSON AT MITSUBISHI AND RECEIVED A PRELIMINARY REPORT. MR. HUDSON INFORMED MR. BEALED THAT MITSUBISHI WAS ABLE TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL AND THAT THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS REQUIRED AT THE TIME. MR. BEAL INFORMED MR. ONE OF THE SIX MANWAY SWING BOLTS HAD A HEAVY BUILD UP OF RUST AND UNTIL CLEANED SWING BOLT COULD APPLIED GORE TEX@ GASKET, CLEANED AND PROPERLY SECURED MANWAY SWING BOLTS WHICH STOPPED LEAK. ON  SUNDAY, 1/10/99, THE TANK CAR WAS OBSERVED DRIPPING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT BY RAILROAD PERSONAL AT THE LIVONIA, LA., YARD. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND INSPECTED BY LOCAL FORCES.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS THE RESULT OF LOOSE NUTS ON TWO OF THE FOUR STUDS THAT SECURE THE FLANGE OF THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE. THE NUTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THIS SECURED THE CAR.  ON MONDAY, 1/11/99, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, T.M. ROBINSON, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  ROBINSON INSPECTED THE CAR AT LIVONIA AND IT APPEARED TO BE SECURE FOR TRANSPORTATION.   ROBINSON THEN CONTACTED MS. CAROL MICK OF UNION CARBIDE AND ADVISED OF ALL THE DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: HAZARDOUS SPILL INCIDENT - DATED: 01/28/99 LOCATION: APPLETON PAPERS, APPLETON, WI TRAILER: #623 DRIVER: CRAIG OWENS.  I RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM MY ASSISTANT KELLY BUENNING AT MY HOME AT APPROXIMATELY 7:10 P.M. ON THURSDAY EVENING 1/28/99.  KELLY ADVISED ME THAT N&M DRIVER CRAIG OWENS HAD JUST REPORTED TO HER AN INCIDENT INVOLVING A LEAKING DRUM WITHIN HIS TRAILER.  APPARENTLY CRAIG OWENS HAD AVOIDED A SERIOUS ACCIDENT (20 MINUTES EARLIER) BY BRAKING EXTREMELY HARD WHILE TRAVELING ON HIGHWAY 41 THROUGH GREEN BAY, WISCONSIN.  CRAIG'S TRAILER WAS LOADED 3/4 FULL ON THE FLOOR, WITH JUST 12 FEET OPEN ON THE BACK.  THE FIRST QUARTER OF HIS TRAILER CONTAINED CRATES ON ONE SIDE  OF THE NOSE AND SKIDS OF PAPER THROUGH OUT THE REST OF THE FIRST QUARTER.  DIRECTLY BEHIND THE CRATES HOWEVER HE PLACED ONE DRUM OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE  SOLUTION.  HE HAD THE DRUM PUSHED UP TIGHT AGAINST THE CRATES IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER, BUT ONE HEAVY SKID OF PAPER WAS LOADED BEHIND IT WITH A GAP OF ABOUT 6 INCHES AWAY FROM THE DRUM.  THE SECOND AND THIRD QUARTER OF THE TRAILER CONTAINED EXTREMELY HEAVY METAL CASTING.  AFTER SPEAKING WITH KELLY BUENNING FOR SEVERAL MINUTES I GAVE HER SOME INITIAL PROCEDURES TO FOLLOW.  SHE CONTACTED ME AGAIN ABOUT 7:20 P.M. WITH THE DRIVER ALSO ON THE LINE.  WE CONTACTED OUR OWN COMPANY EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AND HAD THEM RESPOND TO THE SPILL.  (THIS APPLETON PAPERS LOCATION IS APPROXIMATELY 12 MILES FROM OUR TERMINAL).  I ALSO HAD KELLY CONTACT CHEM-TREC.  CHEM-TREC ADVISED US THAT THE SHIPPER WAS REGISTERED WITH THEM, BUT THEY WERE NOT ABLE TO FAX OVER AN MSDS BECAUSE THIS SHIPPER HAS OVER TWENTY DIFFERENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PRODUCTS WITH THE SAME (UN/NA IDENTIFICATION NUMBER.  IN THE FUTURE, MOTOR CARRIERS WHO HANDLE THIS SHIPPER'S FREIGHT WILL HAVE SERIOUS PROBLEMS OBTAINING AN MSDS BECAUSE THEY DO NOT LIST A PRODUCT NUMBER, TRADE NAME,  OR ANY OTHER DESCRIPTION WHICH DISTINGUISHES THE DIFFERENT PRODUCTS FROM EACH OTHER.  ( I THINK DOT SHOULD FOLLOW UP ON THIS!)  CHEM-TREE EVENTUALLY NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER'S CONTACT AT HOME AND THAT PERSON GAVE US SOME VERBAL INSTRUCTIONS ON HOW TO HANDLE THE SPILL.  THE CONTACT PERSON ALSO ADVISED THAT AN MSDS WAS ATTACHED TO THE DRUM.  (WRITTEN EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION ON THE EXTERIOR OF LEAKING CONTAINERS IN NOT ALWAYS ACCESSIBLE, AND IT DOES NOT AT ALL HELP RESPONSE TEAM MEMBERS DURING A SPILL INCIDENT!!)  SOME SEEPAGE FROM THE LEAKING DRUM STRUCK GROUND SURFACE FROM OUT THE BACK DOOR OF THE TRAILER.  WHILE OUR DRIVER WAS WAITING FOR THE TEAM TO ARRIVE, HE APPLIED ABSORBENT PADS TO AT THE AREA OF THE GROUND THAT WAS CONTAMINATED.   OUR RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED WITHIN 30 MINUTES OF THE CALL.  THEY APPLIED A NEUTRALIZING AGENT TO THE SPILL AREA WITHIN THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER, EXTERIOR OF THE TRAILER, AND GROUND SURFACE.  NO SPILLAGE GOT IN TO ANY SEWERS, DRAIN PIPES, OR WATER WAYS.  THE ORIGINAL PUNCTURED DRUM IS BEING RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE SATURATED ABSORBENT MATERIALS WILL BE DISPOSED

column168: WHILE BEING LOADED ONTO UNITED AIRLINES FLIGHT NUMBER 147/25 JAN 99, THE CAN OF PAINT INSIDE THE SUITCASE BROKE OPEN AND BEGAN LEAKING THICK YELLOW PAINT ONTO THE BELT LOADER AND INTO THE PIT OF THE AIRCRAFT. THE BAG WAS BROUGHT TO UNITED AIRLINE BAGGAGE SERVICE OFFICE. UPON OPENING THE SUITCASE , THE CAN OF PAINT WAS FOUND, WRAPPED IN A TOWEL. THE MARKINGS ON THE LABEL READ "DRESSER YELLOW", "FLAMMABLE", AND "POISON". VERY STRONG AND NAUSEATED FUMES WERE BEING GIVEN OFF FROM THE PAINT AND THE BAG HAD TO BE REMOVED FROM THE OFFICE, AS SEVERAL AGENTS WERE COMPLAINING OF THE SMELL. THE BAG WAS CLOSED BACK UP, PUT INTO SEVERAL LARGE PLASTIC BAGS, AND AND HELD FOR THE FAA TO INVESTIGATE. ON 01FEB99, SPECIAL AGENT STELLA PERAKIS TO INVESTIGATE THIS MATTER AND PHOTOGRAPH THE BAG AND CAN. SHE CALLED BACK ON 02-02-1999 TO ADVISE THE INVESTIGATION WAS COMPLETED

column168: A CUSTOMER OFFERED A BOX (AS CHECKED BAGGAGE) CONTAINING AN AIRCRAFT FUEL PUMP CONTAMINATED WITH FUEL. AT THE TIME THE PACKAGE WAS OFFERED AT THE SAN ANTONIO TICKET COUNTER, THERE WAS NO INDICATION (VERBALLY OR VISUALLY) OF THE BOX'S CONTENTS.THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN DAL WHILE RAMP AGENTS WERE OFF LOADING BAGGAGE IN THE FORWARD BIN OF THE AIRCRAFT AND NOTICED A FUEL SMELL IN THE AIR. THE BOX WAS IDENTIFIED BY THE FUEL SATURATION ON THE CORNER OF THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS TAKEN TO BAGGAGE SERVICE AND WAS INSPECTED. IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN AN AIRCRAFT FUEL PUMP WHICH HAD RESIDUAL FUEL WHICH HAD LEAKED FROM THE INNER BAG TO SATURATE A PORTION OF THE BOX. THE LOCAL CASFO WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD UNTIL THEIR INVESTIGATION WAS COMPLETED. THE CUSTOMER WAS ADVISED THAT THE PACKAGE WOULD BE HELD UNTIL CLEARED BY THE SPECIAL AGENT, AT WHICH TIME HE COULD EITHER SHIP THE PACKAGE AS A HAZ MAT ON A CARGO CARRIER OR ON ANOTHER CARRIER THAT ALLOWS FOR THE SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

THE PACKAGE WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING. EXAMINATION OF THE ALUMINUM CAN REVEALED A PUNCTURED WALL WHICH ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE. THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED. THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

COLLISION, CONRAIL TRAIN MAIL 9, TV 7, AND MGL 16, JANUARY 17,1999, DEARBORN DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 0200 HOURS, SUNDAY, JANUARY 17,1999 ON THE CHICAGO  MAIN LINE AT MP 337 IN STRYKER, OHIO, TV 7 ON APPROACH SIGNAL SLOWING PREPARED TO STOP, MAIL 9 BEHIND ON ONE TRACK WESTBOUND STRUCK THE REAR OF TV 7 DEFLECTING INTO MGL 16 EASTBOUND ON TRACK TWO. THE MAIL 9 ENGINEER, ROGER H. BELL,EMPLOYEE NUMBER 424749, AND CONDUCTOR RAYMOND E. CORELL, EMPLOYEE NUMBER 886434 SUSTAINED FATAL INJURIES. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. APPROXIMATELY TWELVE PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FROM THEIR HOMES FOR APPROXIMATELY TWELVE HOURS. MGL 16 WAS TRANSPORTING EMPTY GONS EASTBOUND WHEN IT WAS STRUCK BY CARS FROM MAIL 9 AND TV 7 AS THEY DERAILED.A TOTAL OF THIRTY -THREE (33) CARS DERAILED. OF THOSE THIRTY-THREE TRAILERS AND CONTAINERS, FOUR (4) CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THE FOLLOWING TWO WERE COMPLETELY DESTROYED: FSTU 625736 ON DTTX 427258 WITH 8 LITERS OF ADHESIVES 3/ UN 1133 / PG II. AND UPOZ 80643 ON TTAX 554528 WITH 1 KILOGRAM OF PETROLEUM GASES LIQUIFIED / 2.1 / UN 1075. UPSZ 847861 ON TTAX 78057 WAS NOT DAMAGED AND THE RAIL CAR WAS UPRIGHT IN-LINE WITH ALL WHEELS ON THE GROUND. CAR WAS RERAILED AND REMOVED FROM THE SITE. FSTZ 636821 ON TTAX 554528 WAS FOUND TO BE LEANING AT APPROXIMATELY 80 DEGREES TO THE EAST ( NOSE OF TRAILER POINTING TO THE SOUTH) WITH THE NOSE TORN AND CRUSHED. DURING CLEAN UP OPERATIONS ON JANUARY 17, 1999 RAIL CAR TTAX 554528 WAS REMOVED UNDER FSTZ 636821 ALLOWING THE TRAILER TO ROLL 90 DEGREES TO ITS SIDE ON THE GROUND AND THE REMAINING PART OF THE TRACK EMBANKMENT. PACKAGES WERE SUCCESSFULLY TRANSFERRED INTO SFTZ 230607 WHICH WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE TRAILVAN FACILITY AT TOLEDO AND FORWARDED TO ITS ORIGINAL DESTINATION. NO PRODUCT LOSS REPORTED.OF THE REMAINING TWENTY-NINE (29) TRAILERS AND CONTAINERS APPROXIMATELY SIX WERE NOT DESTROYED OR SEVERELY DAMAGED. THE REMAINING WERE DESTROYED OR SEVERAL DAMAGED DURING DERAILMENT OR THE FIRE THAT IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWED. THE FIRE AFFECTED CARS DERAILED ON THE NORTH AND SOUTH SIDES, OF THE TRACK. THE LEAD LOCOMOTIVE OF MAIL 9 LANDED ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF #2 MAIN WHILE THE SECOND AND THIRD UNITS LANDED ON THE NORTH SIDE OF #1 MAIN. THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION.

column168: DURING DELIVERY OF GASOLINE AT UNITED DAIRY FARMERS # 107, 3600 BANNING ROAD, CINCINNATI, OHIO, MR. JAMES DICKASON SPILLED GASOLINE. ACCORDING TO HIS INCIDENT REPORT. THE FITTING USED TO MAKE THE DELIVERY  WAS NOT PROPERLY LOCKED ON THIS TANK FILL TUBE, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. MR. DICKASON BEGAN RECOVERY OF THIS PRODUCT. APPROXIMATELY 2-3 GALLONS WENT INTO A STORM DRAIN. OHIO EPA INSTRUCTED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT TO FLUSH THE DRAIN WITH WATER. THIS WAS AN ACCEPTABLE  CLEAN UP. ALL PRESCOTT TANK LINES, INC. DRIVERS WILL RECEIVE A REFRESHER COURSE  ON JOB SPECIFIC TASK INCLUDING PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES WHICH WILL INCLUDE USE OF EQUIPMENT.

column168: FREIGHT HAD BEEN OFFERED FOR DELIVERY TO ITS ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE, REFUSED AND RECONSIGNED, REFUSED AGAIN AND RETURNED TO CARRIER'S FACILITY TO AWAIT INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER. AT TIME OF UNLOADING AT CARRIER'S FACILITY, ONE BAG WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE FAILED. NO SPECIFIC CAUSE COULD BE IDENTIFIED. DAMAGED BAG AND MATERIAL WERE PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK CONTAINER PENDING SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.

WE WERE ATTEMPTING TO RETURN TO PACKAGE TO THE SHIPPER AS THE RECIPIENT WASN'T LOCATED.  THE MATERIAL SPILLED AND WAS RECOVERED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  BASED ON THE CONTENTS, THE SHIPPER, AND PAST ATTEMPTS TO DISCUSS THEIR PACKAGE CONTENTS WITH THIS SHIPPER I SUSPECTED WE HAD AN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  FEDEX HAD RECEIVED AN ANONYMOUS LETTER APPROXIMATELY 24 MONTHS AGO IDENTIFYING SEVERAL SHIPPERS OF UNDECLARED POTASSIUM AND SODIUM HYDROXIDE INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT ALL OF THESE SHIPPERS OPERATED OUT OF MAIL BOXES R US, TYPE OF ESTABLISHMENTS.  THE FAA DUTY OFFICER FOR THE SOUTHERN REGION WAS NOTIFIED.  HE SAID HE'D NOTIFY THE CASFO.   THERE WERE NO MARKINGS LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

column168: I RESPONDED TO OUTBOUND 4, I CONSULTED MY DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET, I CONTAINED THE PACKAGE, I TRANSPORTED THE PACKAGE TO THE DOT CAGE WHERE IT WAS ABSORBED AND NEUTRALIZED AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.

I RESPONDED TO DOOR 31 WEARING ALL PPE AND SUSBA USING DECISION TREE. I IDENTIFIED THE SPILL AS A CORROSIVE BY 5 PART FORM. I TESTED THE PH TO BE 12, USING THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR A CORROSIVE. I NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE, THEN RETESTED THE PH TO BE 7. I THEN ABSORBED THE REMAINING LIQUID WITH CHEMSORB AND PROCESSED THE DAMAGED PORTION THRU THE DMP, THEN RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS DONNA RESOR, PAUL SCHMIDT AND BRUCE SHILTZ DONNED AIR PUFFYING RESPIRATORS WITH HEPA CARTRIDGES, NOMEX SUITS, FIRE HELMETS, FIRE GLOVES, NOMEX HOODS AND RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. THE FIBREBOARD  BOX WAS MARKED, LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS FOLLOWS:FUEL AVIATION TURBINE ENGINE, 3UN1863, IL. THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND 4-1 LITER METAL CANS WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURES. column168: ERNIE SIROTEK, MCTS-OAKLAND, WAS ADVISED THAT GATX 50523 WAS LEAKING FORM THE TOP OF THE CAR. INITIAL REPORTS INDICATED THAT CAR WAS ON TOSCO REFINING COMPANY PROPERTY SINCE TOSCO REFINERY WERE ON THE CAR ATTEMPTING REPAIRS. SITUATION LEADING TO THE INCIDENT INVOLVED TOSCO REFINERY PERSONNEL PERFORMING SAMPLING OPERATIONS BY FILLING A "SAMPLE BOMB" FROM THE SAMPLE LINE. WHILE PULLING THE SAMPLE, THE HOSE FROM THE SAMPLE VALVE TO THE SAMPLE  BOMB BURST. SAMPLE LINE VALVE WAS UNABLE TO BE COMPLETELY CLOSED DUE TO AN ICING CONDITION. TOSCO REFINERY PERSONNEL PERFORMED TEMPORARY REPAIRS THAT ENABLED THE CAR TO SPOTTED INTO THEIR FACILITY FOR OFFLOADING. INCIDENT WAS LATER DETERMINED TO BE ON UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD PROPERTY AS WELL AND WAS SAMPLING THE PRODUCT BEFORE SPOTTING TO THEIR UNLOADING RACK. PROPERTY ISSUES HAVE SINCE BEEN CLARIFIED AND TOSCO REFINING COMPANY  WILL NOT BE DOING ANY FUTURE WORK OF THIS NATURE ON UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD PROPERTY.

FIRST CALL FROM ANSWERING SERVICE STATED THAT MIKE NEEDED DAVID NALL TO CALL HIM-HIS TANKER WAS BROKEN IN-TWO.  CAPTAIN MAY DIRECTED HIS DISPATCH TO CALL AND TELL SOMEONE TO BRING A TANKER SO THAT THE LEAKING TANKER COULD BE OFF LOADED.  WE WERE NOT SURE WHAT WE WOULD FIND WHEN WE ARRIVED ON THE LOCATION, THEREFORE WE CALLED MR. BRADFORD OF BRADFORD WRECKER SERVICE TO RESPOND IN THE EVENT THAT WE NEEDED HIS SERVICES.  DAVID NALL DELIVERED A TRUCK AND TANKER TO THE SITE.  UPON ARRIVAL, DAVID WAS INFORMED BY CAPTAIN MAY THAT WE COULD NOT MOVED THE EQUIPMENT BECAUSE HE WAS CONCERNED THAT THE TANK WOULD RUPTURE.  AT THIS POINT MR. BALL SAID THAT WE WOULD NOT BE ABLE TO PRESSURIZE THE TANK TO TRANSFER THE LOAD.  MR. BALL INFORMED DAVID THAT WE WOULD BE REQUIRED TO STAND BY UNTIL THE TANKER EMPTIED THROUGH THE LEAK.  MR. BALL MADE IT VERY CLEAR THAT THE TANK WOULD BE UNLOADED OR SOLIDIFIED BEFORE WE LEFT THE SIDE.  AFTER ROD AND I HAD AN OPPORTUNITY TO SURVEY THE SITUATION, I REQUESTED THAT MR. BALL ALLOW US TO PUT AIR PRESSURE FROM THE TRUCK COMPRESSOR ON THE TANK TO SEE IF WE COULD INCREASE THE RATE OF FLOW.  THIS WAS NOT SUCCESSFUL.  AT THIS TIME I REQUESTED OF MR. BALL THAT WE BE ALLOWED TO REMOVED THE VALVE FROM THE TANK, SINCE THE VALVE WAS FROZEN AND WOULD NOT ALLOW SULFUR TO FLOW THROUGH.  AFTER REMOVING THE VALVE, WE USED A LONG STEEL ROD TO BREAK THE APPROXIMATELY 6" PLUG IN THE DISCHARGE LINE.  AFTER REMOVAL OF THIS PLUG, THE TRUCK WAS UNLOADED IN APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES.  PRIOR TO THE ARRIVAL OF ANYONE FROM THE TIGER-SUNBELT RESPONSE TEAM, THE MISSISSIPPI DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION SENT IN SOMEONE WITH A BACK-HOE TO BUILD A DAM IN THE DITCH TO CONFINE THE AREA IN WHICH THE SULFUR COULD FLOW.  AFTER THE TRUCK WAS UNLOADED, MR. BALL INFORMED  US THAT WE WOULD NOT BE ALLOWED TO LEAVE THE AREA UNTIL THE SULFUR HAD SOLIDIFIED.  AT THIS POINT, TROOPER BUCKHALTER TOLD US THAT HE COULD GET HIS BROTHER TO WATCH THE SITE FOR US.  WHEN CONTACTED, ANTHONY BUCKHAULTER AGREED TO STAY UNTIL 1:00 A.M. FOR A FEE OF $70.00.  THIS WAS ACCEPTABLE WITH MR. BALL.  WE LEFT THE SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 P.M. SUBJECT:  MAGEE, MISSISSIPPI SULFUR SPILL ON JANUARY 23, 1999 TIGER-SUNBELT DRIVER MIKE STUART LOADED HIS MOLTEN SULFUR TANKER AT JOHNS ENERGY IN JOHNS, MISSISSIPPI FOR A DELIVERY TO MISSISSIPPI PHOSPHATE IN PASCAGOULA, MISSISSIPPI. WHILE TRAVELING SOUTH ON HIGHWAY 49, APPROXIMATELY THREE MILES NORTH OF MAGEE, MISSISSIPPI, MIKE WAS NOTIFIED ON HIS RADIO BY A TRUCK DRIVER THAT HIS TANKER WAS LEAKING. HE IMMEDIATELY PULLER TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD.  MIKE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE ANSWERING SERVICE THAT HE HAD AN EMERGENCY. ATTACHED IS A CHRONOLOGICAL LIST OF THE EVENTS THAT TOOK PLACE IN RESPONSE TO THE SITUATION. AFTER THOROUGH EXAMINATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS INFERIOR DESIGN AND CONSTRUCTION BY THE MANUFACTURER. THE TANK COLLAPSED IN THE DOME LID AREA. INSUFFICIENT STRUCTURAL SUPPORT WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE CAUSE OF THIS FAILURE

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER ON THE IDULA-09, EXTRA UP5016 WEST, LOCATED ON THE MAINLINE AT THE RIMLON SIDING, SP701, MP596, CATHEDRAL CITY, CALIFORNIA. SPECIAL AGENT DENNIS COOKSEY DURING A ROLL BY INSPECTION OF THE TRAIN, OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE ABOVE CONTAINER, AND THE TRAIN STOPPED ON THE MAIN LINE TO INVESTIGATE. AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED FLAMMABLE, AGENT COOKSEY CONTACTED RMCC AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT. MANAGER COOPER WAS CONTACTED AND WHILE ENROUTE TO THE AREA, WAS ADVISED BY AGENT COOKSEY THAT THE NEXT WESTWARD SIDING, SALVIA, MP592, WAS OCCUPIED WITH MAINTENANCE OF WAY EQUIPMENT AND THE TRAIN COULD NOT BE MOVED TO THE SIDING TO PROTECT THE MAINLINE. WHILE DISCUSSING THE PARTICULARS OF THE RELEASE, AGENT COOKSEY ADVISED THE CATHEDRAL CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ARRIVE ON SCENE. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE TRAIN MANAGEMENT DISPATCHERS, WHO WERE ADVISED ALL TRAIN TRAFFIC WOULD BE HALTED PENDING THE OUTCOME OF THE REMEDIATION. MANAGER COOPER MET WITH THE CATHEDRAL CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE RIVERSIDE COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM ON SITE AND ADDRESSED THE HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES ON BOARD THE CONTAINER. AS THE CONTAINER WAS ON THE BOTTOM TIER OF A DOUBLE STACK WELL CAR (TTAX 76542) ACCESS TO THE REAR DOORS WAS OBTAINED AS THE 40 FOOT CONTAINER WAS IN A 48 FOOT CAR. THE RIVERSIDE FIRE DEPARTMENT TEAM MADE ENTRY AND LOCATED ONE DRUM IN THE N OSE OF THE CONTAINER THAT HAD TOPPLED OVER. SINCE MOST OF THE PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED FROM THE DRUM, THEY RIGHTED THE DRUM WHICH STOPPED LEAK. THE RAILROADS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON SITE AND REMOVED THE DRUM, WHERE IT WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK FOR SECUREMENT. SINCE THE ENTIRE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER WAS COVERED WITH PRODUCT, ABSORBENT WAS PLACED THROUGHOUT TO CONTAIN THE FREE LIQUIDS. AN EMPTY DUMMY DRUM WAS PLACED IN THE NOSE TO REPLACE THE DAMAGED DRUM, AND THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE SECURED WITH STRETCH WRAP TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL MOVEMENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS SATISFIED WITH THE CONTAINMENT AND RELEASED THE TRAIN FOR MOVEMENT INTO COLTON. THE CONTAINER WAS DESTINED FOR THE EAST YARD, CITY OF COMMERCE, WHERE IT WAS GROUNDED UPON ARRIVAL. THE FOLLOWING MORNING, RAIL CAR WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER WERE REMOVED AND REWORKED. A CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE LADING IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER DEVELOPED A PALLET OF 4 DRUMS HAD BEEN PLACED IN THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER OF THE CONTAINER WITH NO FORM OF SECUREMENT. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PRACTICE, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PER THE AAR BOE 6C. THERE WAS A VOID TO THE CENTER OF THE CONTAINER, AND THE DAMAGED DRUM HAD TOPPLED FROM THE PALLET AND LEANED INTO THE ADJACENT FREIGHT, WHICH DAMAGED THE DRUM. ONCE THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED, THE LADING WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE LADING WAS PROPERLY SECURED AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT O

DEAN C. COOPER, MGR., CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WA CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT ICTF. MGR., COPPER CONTACTED ICTF SECURITY AND DEVELOPED THE CONTAINER WAS IN THE CHASSIS WEST LOT, STALL # 62. SINCE THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARED TOXIC, THE AREA WAS SECURED TO THROUGH TRAFFIC, WHICH ISOLATED THE CONTAINER PENDING INSPECTION. MGR. COPPER DROVE TO THE ICTF FACILITY, INSPECTED THE EXTERIOR, AND NOTED A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID (LESS THAN ONE PINT) ON THE PAVEMENT NEAR THE RIGHT REAR OF THE CONTAINER. THERE WAS NO ACTIVE LEAK NOTED AT THE TIME OF THE INSPECTION. ABSORBENT WAS PLACED ON THE SPILL AREA AND THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER WAS "DIAPERED' TO CATCH ANY PRODUCT WHILE THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMERS DOCK, WHERE IT COULD BE CONTAINED AND THE INTERIOR INSPECTED. THE PARKING AREA WAS SECURED AROUND THE SPILL SITE, AND THE MAIN AREAS REOPENED TO TRAFFIC. ONCE THE TEAM WAS IN PLACE, THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER WAS OPEN. THE LADING CONSISTED OF 55 GALLON METAL DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED AND SECURED WITH TYGARD FABRIC MATERIAL. IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM, THE CONTENTS WERE MOVED, AND EACH DRUM INSPECTED FOR DAMAGE UPON REACHING THE 3RD ROW FROM THE REAR DOOR, A DRUM ON THE BOTTOM TIER, AGAINST THE RIGHT SIDE WALL, WAS NOTED LEAKING. CLOSER INSPECTION NOTED THE DRUM WAS DEFORMED AT THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP. THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WAS ALSO DEFORMED, WHICH APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED FROM THE DRUM BEING DROPPED. THE DEFLECTION IN THE SIDE WALL OF THE DRUM CAUSED THE LOWER PORTION OF THE ROLLING HOOP TO FOLD DOWN. WHICH RESULED IN A SMALL CRACK IN THE METAL, ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO WEEP OUT. BASED UPON THE WEIGHT OF THE DRUM, IT APPEARS THAT ONLY 2-3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST.THE DRUM WAS PATCHED, PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK, AND SEALED. THE AFFECTED AREAS OF THE CONTAINER DECONNED PER THE MANUFACTUERS RECOMMENDATION, AND THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK IN ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ON TO CONSIGNEE.THE PARKING AREA WAS ALSO ADDRESSED AND REOPENED FOR USE. THE ONE DAMAGED DRUM WAS HELD OUT PENDING RETURN SHIPPING INSTRUCTIONS TO THE MANUFACTURER. BASED UPON THE AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY FRANK VALDEZ,, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR. SUPERVISOR VALDEZ STATED THE ABOVE TANK CAR WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR WHILE IT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS. AS THE CAR WAS PLACARDED CORROSIVE , IT WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM LOOSE SWING BOLTS THAT SECURE THE MANWAY. THE MANWAY IS A STANDARD 8 BOLT PATTERN AND BOLTS 1 THROUGH 4 (CLOCKWISE FROM THE HINGE) COULD BE TURNED BY HAND. A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED PAST THE LOOSE MANWAY, HOWEVER THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR WAS DRY AT THE TIME INSPECTION. THE SWING BOLTS PROPERLY SECURED AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTING WERE INSPECTED, AND FOUND TH BE SECURE. THE CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO INSURE THERE WERE NO ADDITIONAL LEAKS. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. DUE TO THE TO MININMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASE, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: O/E MX950 ON 1-30-99, PASSENGER RAFAEL ALVARADO VALDEZ, TRANSPORTED AS PART OF HIS BAGGAGE A GALLON OF PAINT THINNER.  CONTENTS WERE CONCEALED INSIDE A CARDBOARD BOX.  CONTENTS SPILLED DURING THE FLIGHT, CONTAMINATING THE CENTRAL CARGO COMPARTMENT AS WELL AS ADJACENT BAGGAGE.  THIS PROBLEM WAS DETECTED FIRST BY OGDEN PERSONNEL WHEN BAGS WERE BEING OFF-LOADED, LATER BOX WAS ALSO DETECTED INSIDE THE FIS AREA.  WHEN DETECTED IT WAS ISOLATED TO PROTECT PASSENGERS FROM THE STRONG SMELL AND FUMES THAT WERE BEING RELEASED BY THE CONTENTS.  NO HARM CAUSED TO ANY OF THE PASSENGERS. A COUPLE OF RAMP AGENTS COMPLAINED OF SLIGHT HEADACHES, NOTHING MAJOR.  WHEN MX MANAGEMENT WAS FINALLY MADE AWARE OF THIS SITUATION, PROCEEDED TO PAGE THE PASSENGER THROUGH THE INTERCOM AND ALSO CONTACTED AIRPORT POLICE.  POLICE AND PASSENGER SHOWED UP AT THE TICKET COUNTER.  PASSENGER WAS INTERROGATED.  THE SUSPECT CLAIMED THAT HE WAS NOT AWARE THAT SUCH ITEMS WERE NOT PERMITTED FOR TRANSPORTATION AS CHECKED BAGGAGE.  AIRCRAFT NEEDED TO BE CLEANED AND AIRED OUT, CAUSING A 65 MINS. DELAY.  BOX AND CONTENTS WERE CONFISCATED BY SJPD.  POLICE REPORT HAS ALSO BEEN SUBMITTED.

column168: BRADFORD TAIT ARRIVED AT THE CAMDEN STOP AND GO AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 AM. HE BEGAN HIS DELIVERY IN NORMAL FASHION CONNECTING THE HOSES AND STARTING THE FLOW OF PRODUCT. HE LEFT ONE "EAR" OF HIS VAPOR RECOVERY HOSE UNDONE. HE THEN TURNED HIS BACK ON THE HOSES TO FINISH HIS REQUIRED PAPER WORK. FOR AN UNDETERMINED REASON THE "FLAPPER VALVE" ON THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK CLOSED PREMATURELY. WHEN IT CLOSED IT CAUSED THE FUELING SYSTEM, WHICH IS DESIGNED AS A CLOSED LOOP, TO BACK UP. BECAUSE BRADFORD HAD NOT PROPERLY SECURED BOTH "EARS" OF THE VAPOR RECOVERY HOSE,WHEN THE FUEL BACKED UP IT BEGAN TO LEAK. IT ALSO LEAKED FROM THE POINT OF FUELING FITTING ON TOP OF THE UST INDICATING AN IMPROPERLY FITTING GASKET OR THE FITTING NOT BEING PROPERLY SECURED. AT SOME POINT HE LOOKED AT THE HOSES AND DISCOVERED THAT HE HAD PRODUCT LEAKING ONTO THE GROUND. HE THEN STOPPED THE FLOW OF THE PRODUCT AND USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS BEGAN TO CLEAN THE PRODUCT FROM OFF THE PAVEMENT. AT THIS POINT, A POLICE VEHICLE FROM ROCKPORT ON PATROL WENT PAST THE STOP AND GO AND NOTICED A DARK AREA UNDER THE TANKER. THE ROCKPORT POLICE OFFICER CALLED CAMDEN POLICE DEPT AND RECOMMENDED THAT SOMEONE GO TO THE STORE AND CHECK THE SITUATION. WHEN CAMDEN POLICE ARRIVED THEY DISCOVERED THAT THERE HAD BEEN A SPILL AND CALLED THE FIRE DEPT. THE CALL TO THE FIRE DEPT WAS REPORTED AS A SMALL LEAK. THE FIRE DEPT RESPONDED WITH 3 TRUCKS. THE AUTHORITIES ASSISTED IN REMOVING THE SPILLED PRODUCT FROM THE PAVEMENT. A SMALL AMOUNT WAS FOUND TO HAVE MADE IT INTO THE STORM DRAINS WHICH ARE ABOUT 100FT FROM THE SPILL. THERE WERE ALSO SMALL PUDDLES OF FUEL IN THE AREA. THE REST OF THE SPILL WAS CLEANED BY USING 10 OR 11 BAGS OF FLOOR DRY ON THE AREA. BRADFORD ATTEMPTED TO PHONE THE TRANSPORTATION MANAGER AFTER THE MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN CLEANED BUT THE POLICE DEPT DID NOT LET HIM NEAR HIS TRUCK UNTIL ABOUT 2:45 AM.
